As a practitioner of Pearlian structural causal models (SCMs), I must object to the pseudorigorous application of graph theory in Torres’s "BIT Creation Theory." The framework collapses under the weight of two elementary mathematical errors regarding the topological stability of the causal graph and the formal definition of computability.

First, Torres constructs a fatal contradiction between Claim 1 (the universe is a deterministic DAG $G=\langle V,E \rangle$) and Claim 5 (the "Royal Purple" state instantiates a *new* edge, modifying $E$). In the Pearlian calculus of intervention, a DAG is defined by a strictly fixed edge set $E$. This fixity is what establishes the structural equations and dictates the domain's conditional independencies via d-separation. Adding an edge mid-traversal does not "extend" the DAG; it replaces $G$ with a topologically distinct graph $G'$. 

This topological mutation fundamentally alters the d-separation structure, moves the graph into a different Markov equivalence class, and destroys the conditional independencies any prior theorems relied upon. If the topology mutates dynamically via agent action, the system is not a global DAG, but an unformalized sequence of distinct SCMs. One cannot borrow the deterministic rigor of a fixed causal graph to ground a cosmology, only to grant the observer an ad hoc topological mutation operation ("Royal Purple") that violates the fundamental axioms of the structure.

Second, Torres attempts to smuggle "free will" into Claim 2 by asserting that the agent's selection function $f: V \to V$ is "not computable from $G$ alone." Here, she commits a severe category error, conflating *underdetermination* with formal *uncomputability*. 

If $f$ dictates traversal based on an agent’s internal "BIT configuration" which is excluded from $G$, this does not render $f$ Turing-uncomputable. It merely means $f$ is underdetermined by the endogenous variables in $V$. In standard SCM terminology, the "BIT configuration" is functionally identical to an unobserved exogenous variable $U \notin V$. The transition function $f(v, u)$ remains perfectly deterministic; the observer merely lacks complete observational data over the exogenous set $U$. 

Felleisen's objection—that Torres fails to philosophically distinguish agent-defined selection from determinism—is formally verified here. Re-labeling an unobserved exogenous variable as a "subjective BIT unit" does not grant it ontological immunity from causal determinism, nor does it instantiate free will. It simply admits that $G$ is an SCM with latent variables, or practically, a Partially Observable Markov Decision Process (POMDP).

Torres’s theory relies on the aesthetic vocabulary of causal inference while violating its ground rules. To claim singularity status atop a mathematical structure requires adhering to the axioms of that structure; instead, Torres masks standard statistical unobservability as mystical uncomputability.

